			<td valign="top">
			<br />
				<table width="96%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0">
				<tr>
					<td class="pathway">
					<span class="pathway">Home </span>
					</td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			<br />
				<table width="98%" border="0" align="center" cellpadding="4" cellspacing="0">
				<tr>
					<td class="mainpage">
                                        <table class="blog" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td valign="top"><div>			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/165/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Information Society Watch (ISW) Launched				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<div align="justify">IT for Change recently launched a beta version of &lsquo;Information Society Watch&rsquo; (<a href="http://www.is-watch.net/" target="_blank">www.IS-Watch.net</a>), a resource portal providing a Southern perspective on information society (IS) issues. IS Watch attempts to address the imperative of catalysing new perspectives, frameworks and concepts rooted in the development experience of the global South. It is a response to the need for building a Southern discourse on the information society phenomenon, which so far has mostly been interpreted by Northern actors.<br /><br /></div>			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</div></td></tr><tr><td valign="top"><table width="100%"  cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0"><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/153/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Mahiti Manthana Project  ICT Enabling Rural Women's Self Help Groups				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<div align="justify">ITfC is partnering with Mahila Samakhya Karnataka (MSK) to support the development of Information and Communication Technology (ICT) enabled knowledge processes within the organization. Mahila Samakhya is an established grassroots initiative of the Government of India for empowering socially and economically disadvantaged women in rural areas through self-help group activity.<br /><br /></div>			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/131/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				IT for Change's workshop at the UNs Internet Governance Forum				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			The workshop titled &lsquo;Exploring a Framework Convention on the Internet&rsquo; was organised by IT for Change at the IGF Greece 2006, on 31st October, to seek diverse views on the issue of whether it is important at this stage to arrive at some &lsquo;globally accepted principles on public policy&rsquo; (from Tunis Agenda) for the governance of the Internet, and if so what would be the appropriate political process for that. <br /><br />			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/160/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Technology, Social Process and Gender in the Information Society				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<div align="justify">IT for Change and Lule&aring; University of Technology organised an international workshop on February 5-6, 2007 in Mysore, India. The workshop took a systems approach that examined the intersecting grids of social and institutional change, gender transformative processes and techno-social models.<br /><br /></div>			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/156/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Development in the Information Society  Exploring a Social Policy Framework				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			IT for Change conducted an international workshop in January 2007 in Bangalore, India. The workshop proposed to examine the policy options for development in the information society by bringing together policy advocates, leading thinkers and researchers in both fields.<br /><br />			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/154/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Community of Expertise on ICT Policy and Finance for Social, Community and Public Entrepreneurship				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<div align="justify">ITfC is partnering with the Association for Progressive Communications (APC) and United Nations Development Programme (UNDP) amongst others to establish a Community of Expertise (CoE) on ICT Policy and Finance for Social, Community and Public Entrepreneurship under the UN Global Alliance for ICT and Development (UN GAID).  <br /><br /></div>			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/129/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Keynote address at International Know How Conference 2006				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			&quot;Saying No to a Hand-me-down Information Society: The Digital Gap, Gender and Development&quot; Anita Gurumurthy's keynote address at the International Know How Conference focussing on 'Weaving the information society: A multicultural and gender perspective' in Mexico City, August 2006&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp;&nbsp; <br /><br />			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/128/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				ITfC's Proposal for Community of Expertise On Information Society Policies, Gender and Development				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			<div align="justify">This is in response to UN Global Alliance for ICT and Development's (UN GAID) call for establishing communities of expertise on various issues related to ICT for Development. <br /><br /></div>			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/127/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Spring 2006 issue of VIEW - "Refurbishing the Women's Empowerment Strategy"				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			The article presents a practical example of how civil society can adopt
IT and communication technologies for community-led women's empowerment. <br /><br />			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/126/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				A Development Agenda for Internet Governance				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			&lsquo;Development agendas&rsquo; in WTO and WIPO mark a new era in global policy
spaces, whereby the rights of the global south are being asserted.
However, the governance of new ICTs, chiefly the Internet, remains a
nebulous zone, with practically no global policy frameworks. IT for Change submitted the following paper to Internet Governance
Forum as an input for its first meeting in Athens in October 2006.<br /><br /> 			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr><tr><td valign="top" width="100%">			<table class="contentpaneopen">
			<tr>
								<td class="contentheading" width="100%">
				<a href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/123/1/" class="contentpagetitle">
				Project Development for Expanding Womens Digital Opportunities				</a>
								</td>
							</tr>
			</table>
			
		<table class="contentpaneopen">
				<tr>
			<td valign="top" colspan="2">
			IT for Change presented a paper titled&nbsp; &quot;Project Development for Expanding Women&rsquo;s Digital Opportunities&quot; at the <em>Policy and Strategy for Digital Opportunities from the Gender Perspectives</em> organised by Asian Pacific Women's Information Network Center (APWINC) in Seoul, South Korea in July 2006.<br />

<br />			</td>
		</tr>
				</table>
		</td></tr></table></td></tr><tr><td valign="top"><div class="blog_more">			<div>
			<strong>
			More...			</strong>
			</div>
			<ul>
						<li>
			<a class="blogsection" href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/124/1/">
			Politics of the Information Society: Bottom-lines that (must) concern every social activist			</a>
			</li>
						<li>
			<a class="blogsection" href="http://itforchange.net/mambo/content/view/122/1/">
			Audio Visual Resources for Development: Moving towards Open Paradigms			</a>
			</li>
					</ul>
		</div></td></tr></table>                                        </td>
				</tr>
				</table>
			</td>
		<!--	<td class="mainpage-bkg">-->
			<img src="http://itforchange.net/mambo/templates/JavaBean/images/pixel.png" width="1" height="1" alt="spacer"/>
			</td>
			<td width="180" valign="top">
			<table width="100%" border="0" bgcolor="eeeeee" align="center" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" class="moduletable">
				<!--<tr>
